  "lesson_id": "lesson_particle_nomi",
  "lesson_title": "The Logic of Exclusion: Restrictive Particle のみ (nomi)",
  "lesson_summary": "In this final lesson of Unit 7, we explore the particle のみ (nomi), which acts as a logical 'filter' to isolate a specific subject or condition, functioning much like the Chinese character '唯' (wéi).",
  "grammar_point": "particle_nomi",
  "grammar_explanation": {
    "concept": "The particle のみ (nomi) is a restrictive particle used to limit the scope of a statement to the word immediately preceding it. It translates to 'only,' 'just,' or 'nothing but.' In a logical sense, it creates a set where only one element satisfies the condition of the verb.",
    "formation": "[Noun/Verb/Particle] + のみ",
    "variations": [
      "のみならず (not only... but also)",
      "のみこそ (only indeed - combined with emphasis)"
    ],
    "common_confusions": [
      "vs. ばかり (bakari): While both can mean 'only,' のみ is more formal and strictly restrictive in classical Japanese, whereas ばかり often implies 'approximately' or 'nothing but' in a more emotive sense."
    ]
  },
  "teaching_sequence": [
    {
      "type": "introduction",
      "content": "We have spent this unit looking at particles that add emotional weight or focus (like 'zo' and 'koso'). Now, we conclude with a particle that performs a precise logical operation: exclusion. The particle <span class='highlight'>のみ (nomi)</span> functions exactly like the Chinese '唯' (wéi) or '独' (dú). It tells the reader: 'Ignore everything else; the statement applies only to this specific thing.'"
